scenes.label: *start
texts: I heard a sound loud enough to pierce through the roar of my graper motor.
Acting on instinct, I swerved away from it and headed south on Loop 7.
Seriously? That was a goddamn gunshot!
Damn it! I feel like they're leading us right where they want us to be!
I'd lost the drones, but I was still running into armored cars as I raced along the residential area's winding paths.
And now I was getting pushed onto Loop 7—an actual main road.
You're dealing with the army. I wouldn't be surprised if they were monitoring you through military sats.
That'd mean I couldn't get away no matter what I did.
This constant hacking shit, too... God, this is annoying!
This must've been the army too. They were doing everything in their power to hijack my graper's systems.
It was forcing me to change my ride's address manually every second or so.
Sure, I'd seen stuff like this in the amateur graper races and been forced to do high-speed setting management...
But there was a world of difference between a casual race and a goddamn army chase! This was way too tense!
I couldn't relax for a single second, and there was no telling how long these attacks would last...
Or how long I'd be able to keep focus...!
I felt Momo's warmth on my back.

scenes.label: *kaisou
texts: We were going so fast that she was desperately clinging to me for dear life.
This strange girl in weird clothing I'd met barely two hours ago...
...was the reason I was being chased by the goddamn army, of all things.
I had no reason to go through all this for her...
...but there's no way I was just gonna leave her behind. It'd be against my creed...against my convictions! That wasn't how I rolled!
But I also had no idea where to go at this point.
All I could do was dodge the hacks and keep the chase going.
You're past the Koenji blockade. Let's hope they didn't account for the roads to the south of it.
If they were watching me from space anyway, then taking the fast route on Loop 7 made more sense than winding through the residential streets.
It was probably down to the blockades, but thankfully, the roads were empty.
The straight two-lane road was well-lit, so I could see pretty far into the distance.
The attacks on the graper's systems continued, but I managed to fend them off.
We could actually get out of this.
...though they blended in with the scenery speeding by, a set of red letters caught my eye.

scenes.label: *polonsave1
texts: The street lights lit them right up.
Why some weird graffiti on the pedestrian bridge caught my attention like that was beyond even me.
But it was enough to throw me off for a few seconds.
I tried to hit the brakes, but...
We passed right under the Shinjuku route.
I lost control of the graper instantly.
I was driving way too fast when it happened.
There was nothing I could do to maintain balance.

scenes.label: *storehis
texts: A chopper was flying in the night sky overhead, with its searchlight shining down.
Multiple armored cars hidden with <tips,14,active camo> revealed themselves on the road I thought was empty.
I had no idea things would get this wild.
And I'd never guess that the center of all this—the person the army was after—was this one girl.
Our eyes met as we flew through the air.
I felt like white noise overcame my vision...
And the next moment, I crashed into the road.
I tried as hard as I could to stand up.
My body was aching all over. I wouldn't be surprised if bones were broken.
My graper was basically a pile of scrap.
She was lying a short distance away. Her head was bleeding, and she wasn't conscious.
I tried to crawl over to her.
Before I reached her, a load of armored cars pulled up, and we found ourselves surrounded by soldiers.
Finally, with perfect timing, they were joined by the tatted baldy-builder from before.
As I lay there on the asphalt, he looked down at me with ice-cold eyes.
I tried to say something back, but the pain was so bad I couldn't talk.
Suddenly, a strong wind racked my body.
Looking up, I saw a bright light.
Both of those things were from the chopper, now landing while making ear-tearing sounds.
Once it landed, two people climbed out.
One was a mean-looking boy with a bow-tie. He couldn't have been older than a middle-schooler.
The other was a long-haired man with a pale complexion.
That was when the baldy's old-fashioned transceiver rang out.
Captain, we were ordered to retreat.
Retreat? That's absurd. What is the government thinking?
The boy, who was listening to that exchange, shrugged his shoulders.
I suppose this was too much of a spectacle.
No matter. We secured the woman.
He spoke in an apathetic tone, then issued an order to the surrounding soldiers.
Hey, get her on the chopper!
They took Momo's unconscious body and ran over to the chopper.
They were followed by the bow-tie kid and the long-haired man.
I tried to raise my voice, but the pain silenced me.
Fighting the pain, I tried to reach out, but my hand was nowhere near close enough.
The chopper took off. It all happened so fast.
I wanted to cry out in frustration, but my body couldn't even manage a yell.
The only ones left were me, still crawling on the ground, and the soldiers, with that tatted baldy-builder among them.
The police are coming. We should withdraw.
Forget everything you saw today, kid, or else you'll be locked up for life.
"Forget" my ass... I'm gonna spread this...\nall over the net... The whole world's gonna know...about you fuckers!
He suddenly grabbed me by the chest.
He was strong, scary strong. I couldn't escape his grip, no matter how hard I struggled.
He was about to kick my ass, wasn't he? I felt like if I experienced any more pain I'd end up paralyzed.
I clenched my teeth as hard as I could.
I spat the blood in my mouth straight at his face, to taunt him.
Go ahead...another one in the stomach. Heh.
He went for my face instead.
He sent me flying, and I found myself rolling along the road...
But that was exactly what I'd been waiting for.
Ignoring the pain, I used the momentum from the fall to twist my body, and set off running in the opposite direction.
I looked around, barely able to keep myself from collapsing.
The Shinjuku route was above me, and the Koshu-Kaido underpass below.
I didn't have time to think, so I just dropped down.

texts: The soldiers had distanced themselves from the car to avoid getting hit, but they were readying their guns.
Seeing that erased any hesitation I might've had.
I jumped into the passenger seat.
The tatted baldy-builder was standing right in front of the car, but that didn't stop the driver from flooring it.
The baldhead dove sideways right before impact, leaving the road clear for us.
Once we were out of the underpass, we took the road leading to Shinjuku.
Sitting in the cramped rear seat was a girl who must've been in elementary school.
Though I understood the words she was saying, I couldn't make sense of her appearance. She looked just like a porcelain doll.
The girl was pointing at something beyond the rear glass—an armored car coming after us.
Man, this isn't even fair. We can't lose 'em in this hunk of garbage.
Hey, Oz, can I take care of them? Can I, can I, can I? Nonno's real good at this!
The girl calling herself "Nonno" went down to the rear seat foot area, and...
...She spoke in a cutesy voice as she held up a 60cm long cylinder. It looked a lot like...a rocket launcher?
She saw that I was looking at it, and smiled.
This is my Beary-Airy! I made it myself! Go ahead, tell me how awesome I am!
She stuck her torso out of the sunroof, readied her rocket launcher, and targeted the armored car.
For real for real, that's the deal!
Was I about to watch a child take on the army solo?! When did Japan become such a lawless wasteland?!

scenes.label: *chk_rocket
texts: The rocket shot through the air, a trail of white smoke snaking behind it.
It hit the armored car...at least, I thought it had.
But it actually exploded right in front of it.
Huh? You can't tell by looking? They're fireworks! Loads of them! SHWOO! BOOM! BLAST THE POWDER KEGS!
I'm surprised you know what powder kegs are.
I don't know what they are!
So it was just a bluff...
It looked like it was enough, though.
The armored car's driver must've panicked, 'cause the thing smashed into a guardrail, lost balance, and stopped in its tracks.
We were putting some distance between us and them.
Soon enough, I couldn't make out any of the soldiers inside.
The last two hours had been insane...
It was hard to believe how little time had passed since Momo called out to me at Sun Plaza.
You okay? You sure don't look it.
He's like a crumply wet rag!♪
My name's Oz. I'm one of Nakano's...well...how should I put it? Kind of a detective.
The li'l lady behind us is...
The li'l lady behind you is Nonno! I'm a virtuoso!
She didn't say anything else, so I had no idea what kind of virtuoso she was.
So, what happened to the li'l lady you were running away with?
R-right! They took Momo away! I gotta go save her!
Took her away? The chopper, huh?
Nonno, do you know where it went?
From the direction, it looked like it went to Haneda Airport! And lots of people online are saying they saw it!
Oh yeah, a chopper landed in a residential area. There's no way that wouldn't get attention online.
Th-then take me to Haneda! Please!
What exactly is goin' on between those army folks and you two?
By the time we snuck past all our pursuers and arrived at Haneda Airport, an hour had passed since Momo was taken away.
The chopper with Momo onboard had landed on the tarmac for private jets, slightly outside the actual airport.
Staying hidden, we strained to see what was going on inside, and caught a glimpse of Momo being handed over to some mysterious foreigners.
Seriously, who is that li'l lady?
It sounded like the government was ordering the army.
Did the Vatican pressure the government into mobilizing the army? Then why's that brat involved in this?
Damn, can't tell who's got authority over what.
But I didn't care if it was the government or the Vatican.
Momo was about to be taken outside Japan. There's no way I could help her if that happened.
You dumbass. We're in an airport. Security'll grab ya the moment you walk in.
And the army might be hidin' somewhere close-by.
You're not gonna be able to do shit on your own. You'll just get yourself killed.
So...what? Did I have to resign myself to twiddling my thumbs as I watched it happen?
I'd just met her, and I didn't know anything about her. She was basically a stranger to me.

texts: There were so many people at Sun Plaza, but out of all of them, she called out to me.
I'd told her I'd help her. I'd told her she could count on me.
I couldn't even protect one girl.
Frustration, anger, and shame swirled chaotically inside my head.
I felt like tearing out my hair, like screaming until my throat was dry, and cursing myself to hell.
I punched the airport's fence, over and over.
But the frustration wouldn't go away.
I was overcome by an explosion of emotion.

Those are the words I saw earlier.
I didn't have my optic recording on back then.
